	<tr>
	
		<td class="msg_user_cell" width="150" valign=top>
		
			 









<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=135075'  class="auth_text"  style="font-weight:bold;" >	
<span style='color:#CC6600;font-weight:bold; '>Grizzlesnozz</span></a>
			<br>
			
			<span style="font-size: 8pt;">
			Master<br>
			
				Posts: 477<br>
				
				Registered: 02-27-2006
				
			</span>
			


			
			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=135075'>







</a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=warriorbalance&message.id=19613#M19613">226</a> of 312
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 405 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			1. The difference is a raid covers an area of ground. Should i be busy and unable to close with the mob before it enters camp i will not have built aggro on it. During that time a cleric could become a corpse waiting to happen. Knights and even rangers, beats and other ranged aggro generators need to control aggro on these mobs until designated tanks get on them. Warriors lack control here and always have. Trust me I MA'd for a long time, i know what it's like to swim to the next unmezzable entering the raid to murder the cleric, or, wade to it while snared, or still be getting summoned to my last mob, or, simply having ae taunt down and too much aggro is built up and i'm too late. It happens.<br><br>Raid aggro is like an area effect radiating outwards. If a lot of healing is going on inside the raid this can build up on a mob from some distance away and certainly it can be significant by the time a warrior gets to it. A knight can be building aggro right away regardless of his position, mob distance and any other factors nhibiting his closure with the mob. A knight can usually force a mob to close with him, a warrior does not share anywhere enar that level of strength and range, although, it has improved. Knights are better at this.<br><br>2. The MA is not a twit if he calls assist on a mob because he knows it's controlled /tanked. The MA doesn't necessarily have to have control himself if healing support is adequete. It is however a very poor decision on a knight MA's part in most circumstances when he calls assist on an add he has reason to be unsure of control on. As a matter of routine when I'm not busy i move through camp and taunt bazu mezzed mobs. I expect other tanks to do the same knight, or, war. The better your raid force is and the addition of coa+ chanter abilities makes this stuff a lot easier. it still remains the MA's job to control dps so as to direct it at tanked mobs when necessary. You suggested the dps simply assisted the MA without any indication he was ready, without giving him any time to be ready. That is weak raid activity and in ahrd content it's likely to cost you.<br><br>3. Newp, there is plenty of content that snares and roots tanks and probably more coming given the going trend. Knights can take and hold aggro reasonably well from a distance, warriors cannot. I'm not sure what kind of raid experience you have, but, this is not a new trick. Raids even use knights to build aggro on rooted mobs hehe.<br>You may have meant SPELL SLOW. However, you replied to me and it should have been obvious what I meant when i said slow. I don't give a crap if I'm spell slowed along with the raid.<br><br>4. Even most knights I talk to agree their aggro generation is superior at the beginning of a fight. Like i said the exception could possibly be if we actually engage at the same time which normally shouldn't happen with the incoming adds I described. Our knights have those aggroed while they are still well away from the raid as per their norm. And IF I bazu, cyclone and proc well. Knight aggro is very strong at the start of a fight. If they are actually going hard i usually do not get aggro until I taunt immediately followed by bazu. Overtime with some luck i may over take them and this part is debatable... I believe that if the knight is going max aggro he will usually still win. I know i have knights in our raids i will not take aggro from when they wish to keep it without taunt. However, we never test that on long lasting big mobs. I can tell you when we had knights tank boss mobs before they had np keeping aggro from us with our hate weapons out. Not even one single twitch on some knights... ever. They did this much quicker and locked aggro much tighter than any warrior i've ever seen. Now I haven't done that as routine since Time. We did have dbotw's and FB's augged up then and were using them easily to dps while knights tanked. Again i have enver seen that degree of aggro lock since. We didn't have cyclone then though.<br><br>5. Why would your MA role fade away?<br>3.<br><div></div>	
		</td></tr>
