			<br>
			
				<img src="/i/p.gif" height=8 width=150 border=0 alt=""><br>
				
			<a href='/eq/view_profile?user.id=65091'>







<img src="http://i63.photobucket.com/albums/h150/BertyB27/avatarnew.jpg" border=0 alt=""/></a><br>
			


			
			<p>
			






<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=warriorbalance&message.id=19627#M19627">234</a> of 312
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 356 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div>"The difference is a raid covers an area of ground. Should i be busy and
unable to close with the mob before it enters camp i will not have
built aggro on it. During that time a cleric could become a corpse
waiting to happen. Knights and even rangers, beats and other ranged
aggro generators need to control aggro on these mobs until designated
tanks get on them. Warriors lack control here and always have. Trust me
I MA'd for a long time, i know what it's like to swim to the next
unmezzable entering the raid to murder the cleric, or, wade to it while
snared, or still be getting summoned to my last mob, or, simply having
ae taunt down and too much aggro is built up and i'm too late. It
happens.<br><br>Raid aggro is like an area effect radiating outwards.
If a lot of healing is going on inside the raid this can build up on a
mob from some distance away and certainly it can be significant by the
time a warrior gets to it. A knight can be building aggro right away
regardless of his position, mob distance and any other factors
nhibiting his closure with the mob. A knight can usually force a mob to
close with him, a warrior does not share anywhere enar that level of
strength and range, although, it has improved. Knights are better at
this."<br>-&nbsp; Grizzlesnozz<br><br><br><b>The mob should not regularly be in the casters for several reasons, probably the most important being visibility, another being effective utilization of proximity mods. At no point in time should you be so stressed as an MA that you are not able to pick up an incomming mob without a long range aggro spell. I realize that your guild may regularly put that stress on your MA's, but it's simply much more efficient and safe to have another tank waiting to pick up that mob. I've been MA'ing as a knight for as long as I've been raiding and there have been quite obvious high and low points in its effectiveness that people often miss being locked into stereotypes. PoP was a high point, GoD (especially Uqua) was a low point, OoW (especially CoA) was a high point, and DoD/PoR have been another low point. <br><br>Raid aggro is not an area effect at its best, it's a line or barrier&nbsp; that protects the class within. I play a knight MA, and I'm telling you that I can not force a mob close to me in the more recent expansions.&nbsp; It just doesn't work. The MA, whether it be a warrior or a knight should be in front of the raid ready to pick up mobs for best results. If a mob warps, or comes in with a runspeed buff, warriors actually end up with a strong advantage because of their instant although limited range abilities.<br><br></b>"2. The MA is not a twit if he calls assist on a mob because he knows it's
controlled /tanked. The MA doesn't necessarily have to have control
himself if healing support is adequete. It is however a very poor
decision on a knight MA's part in most circumstances when he calls
assist on an add he has reason to be unsure of control on. As a matter
of routine when I'm not busy i move through camp and taunt bazu mezzed
mobs. I expect other tanks to do the same knight, or, war. The better
your raid force is and the addition of coa+ chanter abilities makes
this stuff a lot easier. it still remains the MA's job to control dps
so as to direct it at tanked mobs when necessary. You suggested the dps
simply assisted the MA without any indication he was ready, without
giving him any time to be ready. That is weak raid activity and in ahrd
content it's likely to cost you."<br>- Grizzlesnozz<br><br><b>That's the thing, I'm not unsure when i call assist on a mezzed mob. I may wait until I've personally broken the mez, but I'm confident that the rest of the raid has done its job and that mob is not going to run to an enchanter. Resting the weight of the raid on top of the MA as you've described doing is inefficient and leads to burn out. I at no point in time suggested the raid assisted without a call btw. I'm really not sure where you get some of those implications.<br><br></b>"3. Newp, there is plenty of content that snares and roots tanks and
probably more coming given the going trend. Knights can take and hold
aggro reasonably well from a distance, warriors cannot. I'm not sure
what kind of raid experience you have, but, this is not a new trick.
Raids even use knights to build aggro on rooted mobs hehe.<br>You may
have meant SPELL SLOW. However, you replied to me and it should have
been obvious what I meant when i said slow. I don't give a crap if I'm
spell slowed along with the raid."<br>- Grizzlesnozz<br><br><b>Do you just not understand proximity mods? I can go into greater detail if you'd like. I can build as much aggro as I want standing away from the mob, but I'm not going to get it to come to me, and in the mean time it's beating on someone else. It takes the warrior and the knight the same time to get within melee range of the mob, and neither is going to get aggro before doing so. The fact that the knight can build aggro from a distance offers him no benefit. I didn't "mean" spell slow. I said spell slow. You not picking up on the fact that I countered your example of slow with the example of spell slow is no fault of mine.<br><br></b>"4. Even most knights I talk to agree their aggro generation is superior
at the beginning of a fight. Like i said the exception could possibly
be if we actually engage at the same time which normally shouldn't
happen with the incoming adds I described. Our knights have those
aggroed while they are still well away from the raid as per their norm.
And IF&nbsp; I bazu, cyclone and proc well. Knight aggro is very strong at
the start of a fight. If they are actually going hard i usually do not
get aggro until I taunt immediately followed by bazu.&nbsp; Overtime with
some luck i may over take them and this part is debatable... I believe
that if the knight is going max aggro he will usually still&nbsp; win. I
know i have knights in our raids i will not take aggro from when they
wish to keep it without taunt. However, we never test that on long
lasting big mobs. I can tell you when we had knights tank boss mobs
before they had np keeping aggro from us with our hate weapons out. Not
even one single twitch on some knights... ever. They did this much
quicker and locked aggro much tighter than any warrior i've ever seen.
Now I haven't done that as routine since Time. We did have dbotw's and
FB's augged up then and were using them easily to dps while knights
tanked. Again i have enver seen that degree of aggro lock since. We
didn't have cyclone then though."<br>- Grizzlesnozz<br><br><b>On a normal incomming mob, a knight will have gotten one spell off (a wise choice would be AFoJ) for 1800 or so hate. He normally won't be casting his 2nd spell until the mob is in camp. Slightly before the mob is in camp, a warrior might have shot an arrow, hit his Vish shoulders, mock, cyclone, and before the knight has finished casting, a round or two of melee for around 4000+ hate. Obviously it would be foolish of a warrior to do that on common trash mobs, but the capacity remains, and a single mock or bazu is more than enough to secure their aggro over dps and debuffers. That combined with very consistant proc and melee aggro is as good a lock as any knight could hope for. There is less difference between intial and sustained aggro than most would have you believe, and the fact is that knights and warriors have aggro close enough that they will regularly bounce aggro for many minutes.</b><br><br><span **froglok="" text-decoration="" underline=""><span **froglok="" font-weight="" bold=""></span></span><a href="../view_profile?user.id=135075" target="top" class="auth_text" **froglok="" font-weight="" bold=""><span **froglok="" color="" rgb(204="" 102="" 0="" font-weight="" bold=""></span></a><div></div>"5. Why would your MA role fade away?"<br>- Grizzlenozz<br><br><b>The role itself is not fading, we're very capable of preforming it sub-end zone PoR. Our preference in that role however is very quickly fading if not already gone. Most guilds that I've talked to see no necessity in knight MA's and simply assign a warrior, paladin, or sk indescriminantly as circumstance, gear, and skill dictate.</b><br><p>Message Edited by BertyB on <span class=date_text>05-16-2006</span> <span class=time_text>04:42 PM</span>
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
