			>
			<div></div><div><span><br><blockquote><hr>BertyB wrote:<br><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div><div></div>&quot;The difference is a raid covers an area of ground. Should i be busy and unable to close with the mob before it enters camp i will not have built aggro on it. During that time a cleric could become a corpse waiting to happen. Knights and even rangers, beats and other ranged aggro generators need to control aggro on these mobs until designated tanks get on them. Warriors lack control here and always have. Trust me I MA'd for a long time, i know what it's like to swim to the next unmezzable entering the raid to murder the cleric, or, wade to it while snared, or still be getting summoned to my last mob, or, simply having ae taunt down and too much aggro is built up and i'm too late. It happens.<br><br>Raid aggro is like an area effect radiating outwards. If a lot of healing is going on inside the raid this can build up on a mob from some distance away and certainly it can be significant by the time a warrior gets to it. A knight can be building aggro right away regardless of his position, mob distance and any other factors nhibiting his closure with the mob. A knight can usually force a mob to close with him, a warrior does not share anywhere enar that level of strength and range, although, it has improved. Knights are better at this.&quot;<br>- Grizzlesnozz<br><br><br><b>The mob should not regularly be in the casters for several reasons, probably the most important being visibility, another being effective utilization of proximity mods. At no point in time should you be so stressed as an MA that you are not able to pick up an incomming mob without a long range aggro spell. I realize that your guild may regularly put that stress on your MA's, but it's simply much more efficient and safe to have another tank waiting to pick up that mob. I've been MA'ing as a knight for as long as I've been raiding and there have been quite obvious high and low points in its effectiveness that people often miss being locked into stereotypes. PoP was a high point, GoD (especially Uqua) was a low point, OoW (especially CoA) was a high point, and DoD/PoR have been another low point.<br><br>Raid aggro is not an area effect at its best, it's a line or barrier that protects the class within. I play a knight MA, and I'm telling you that I can not force a mob close to me in the more recent expansions. It just doesn't work. The MA, whether it be a warrior or a knight should be in front of the raid ready to pick up mobs for best results. If a mob warps, or comes in with a runspeed buff, warriors actually end up with a strong advantage because of their instant although limited range abilities.<br><br></b>&quot;2. The MA is not a twit if he calls assist on a mob because he knows it's controlled /tanked. The MA doesn't necessarily have to have control himself if healing support is adequete. It is however a very poor decision on a knight MA's part in most circumstances when he calls assist on an add he has reason to be unsure of control on. As a matter of routine when I'm not busy i move through camp and taunt bazu mezzed mobs. I expect other tanks to do the same knight, or, war. The better your raid force is and the addition of coa+ chanter abilities makes this stuff a lot easier. it still remains the MA's job to control dps so as to direct it at tanked mobs when necessary. You suggested the dps simply assisted the MA without any indication he was ready, without giving him any time to be ready. That is weak raid activity and in ahrd content it's likely to cost you.&quot;<br>- Grizzlesnozz<br><br><b>That's the thing, I'm not unsure when i call assist on a mezzed mob. I may wait until I've personally broken the mez, but I'm confident that the rest of the raid has done its job and that mob is not going to run to an enchanter. Resting the weight of the raid on top of the MA as you've described doing is inefficient and leads to burn out. I at no point in time suggested the raid assisted without a call btw. I'm really not sure where you get some of those implications.<br><br></b>&quot;3. Newp, there is plenty of content that snares and roots tanks and probably more coming given the going trend. Knights can take and hold aggro reasonably well from a distance, warriors cannot. I'm not sure what kind of raid experience you have, but, this is not a new trick. Raids even use knights to build aggro on rooted mobs hehe.<br>You may have meant SPELL SLOW. However, you replied to me and it should have been obvious what I meant when i said slow. I don't give a crap if I'm spell slowed along with the raid.&quot;<br>- Grizzlesnozz<br><br><b>Do you just not understand proximity mods? I can go into greater detail if you'd like. I can build as much aggro as I want standing away from the mob, but I'm not going to get it to come to me, and in the mean time it's beating on someone else. It takes the warrior and the knight the same time to get within melee range of the mob, and neither is going to get aggro before doing so. The fact that the knight can build aggro from a distance offers him no benefit. I didn't &quot;mean&quot; spell slow. I said spell slow. You not picking up on the fact that I countered your example of slow with the example of spell slow is no fault of mine.<br><br></b>&quot;4. Even most knights I talk to agree their aggro generation is superior at the beginning of a fight. Like i said the exception could possibly be if we actually engage at the same time which normally shouldn't happen with the incoming adds I described. Our knights have those aggroed while they are still well away from the raid as per their norm. And IF I bazu, cyclone and proc well. Knight aggro is very strong at the start of a fight. If they are actually going hard i usually do not get aggro until I taunt immediately followed by bazu. Overtime with some luck i may over take them and this part is debatable... I believe that if the knight is going max aggro he will usually still win. I know i have knights in our raids i will not take aggro from when they wish to keep it without taunt. However, we never test that on long lasting big mobs. I can tell you when we had knights tank boss mobs before they had np keeping aggro from us with our hate weapons out. Not even one single twitch on some knights... ever. They did this much quicker and locked aggro much tighter than any warrior i've ever seen. Now I haven't done that as routine since Time. We did have dbotw's and FB's augged up then and were using them easily to dps while knights tanked. Again i have enver seen that degree of aggro lock since. We didn't have cyclone then though.&quot;<br>- Grizzlesnozz<br><br><b>On a normal incomming mob, a knight will have gotten one spell off (a wise choice would be AFoJ) for 1800 or so hate. He normally won't be casting his 2nd spell until the mob is in camp. Slightly before the mob is in camp, a warrior might have shot an arrow, hit his Vish shoulders, mock, cyclone, and before the knight has finished casting, a round or two of melee for around 4000+ hate. Obviously it would be foolish of a warrior to do that on common trash mobs, but the capacity remains, and a single mock or bazu is more than enough to secure their aggro over dps and debuffers. That combined with very consistant proc and melee aggro is as good a lock as any knight could hope for. There is less difference between intial and sustained aggro than most would have you believe, and the fact is that knights and warriors have aggro close enough that they will regularly bounce aggro for many minutes.</b><br><br><span><span></span></span><a target="top" href="../view_profile?user.id=135075"><span> 102=&quot;&quot; 0=&quot;&quot; font-weight=&quot;&quot; bold=&quot;&quot;&gt;</span></a><div></div>&quot;5. Why would your MA role fade away?&quot;<br>- Grizzlenozz<br><br><b>The role itself is not fading, we're very capable of preforming it sub-end zone PoR. Our preference in that role however is very quickly fading if not already gone. Most guilds that I've talked to see no necessity in knight MA's and simply assign a warrior, paladin, or sk indescriminantly as circumstance, gear, and skill dictate.</b><br><p>Message Edited by BertyB on <span class="date_text">05-16-2006</span><span class="time_text">04:42 PM</span><br></p><hr></blockquote>Your just making stuff up now.<br><br>I said it was a knight strength to pick up those adds. I said that they routinely grab them on incoming. That doesn't mean it's always gone well, or, raids I have been in have never been in trouble because of loose add aggro. As MA you have never had a target come into camp that you need to get on fast, or, switch dps too? Trust me it's easier to do this as a Knight. One of the most obvious zones where this stands out is POW. The fact that you've been MAing for as slong as you've been raiding undermines the point of your argument here. Knights make good MA's in a lot of content. that was my point remember?<br><br>You are lying, or, don't know better with your statement about not being able to force regular trash mobs to close with you. I can stand out in front of a raid and below a mob on incoming. 9 times out of 10 a knight behind the whole raid could aggro and pull that mob right past me and the raid if he wanted. Of course this would be situational, however, our knights do this constantly. Normally during clearing these days i watch other folks play and manage stuff i haven't had time to. It's routine for me to tgt incoming mobs and watch who picks them up. of course tanks normally try to handle mobs in front of the raid. Are you telling me you guys never push, that aggro is never lost? I Almost every single mob has distance aggro lock from a knight and moves to the player until it gets to the raid where it is generally tank mezzed until mezzed, or, dps is called onto it. It's a bloody rare thing in an open area with decent los when everything is going well that a knight doesn't have aggro on a mob still far away from our raid. Of course its the exceptions that threaten the raid that really count, but, knight distance aggro is obvious. Knights routinely force mobs to close with them in dpob and coa in our raids, how's that for recent. They've been doing it since i've been raiding.<br><br>In my plane of water example an add entering the raid area at range can be very difficult for a warrior to control position on which it being dragged away by debuffers and heal aggro. yeah, in a perfect world it won't happen, but, it does. A knight doesn't have that problem. he can most often flip targets and without even physically seeing it aggro it and draw it to him. I have watched knights do this kinda stuff so many times it's not funny. i have no idea where your problem lies.<br><br>There are raids where you need to be sure and where it's unlikely that other tanks will have your aggro handled. That is why we have assist calls, to foucs the dps in a timely manner. Otherwise yeah you could throw out assist calls and they could just assist the MA whenver they want and blow stuff up. If you always do that dps are going to get killed for it. In some raids it would practically equal auto wipe.<br><br>I did not make an argument about spell slow, just slow. To which you did not reply with spell slow, you replied with the word slow to my already made statement. Is the implication of that lost on you?<br><br>I understand prox aggro mods fine. If the raid is totally static and there is no healing going on atm, even i can usually stand behind folks and draw an incoming add with bellow through other people. My range and power to do so is just far less than a knight's and local aggro will draw the mobs attention from me more quickly. We have been talking about trash mobs here not bosses. Obviously some mobs like undead tend to have higher prox aggro. i doubt you will teach me anything about it, ty tho.<br><br>No actually, bazu,or, mock are not enough aggro to pull a mob past a debuffer wit confidence who has slowed in most cases. A knight can do this np though. Ours do it all the time.<br><br>Our knights have stronger initial aggro on mobs and always have.<br><br>Erm, you can use anyone you want to MA, knights are just well suited to the role in a lot of content.<br><br><br><br><br></span></div>	
